{
  "id": "school.word-factory",
  "order": 8,
  "title": {
    "en": "The Word Factory",
    "uz": "So'z fabrikasi"
  },
  "blurb": "Four suffixes that multiply every word you learn",
  "estimatedMinutes": 3,
  "prerequisites": [
    "school.suffixes"
  ],
  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "Four bricks that multiply your vocabulary",
      "body": [
        "A few suffixes build new words so predictably that every word you learn becomes a whole family. **-chi** makes the person who does it. **-li** means having it. **-siz** means without it. **-lik** makes the abstract idea of it."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "futbolchi",
          "english": "footballer",
          "breakdown": [
            "futbol",
            "chi"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "football",
            "person who does"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "aqlli",
          "english": "clever — “having mind”",
          "breakdown": [
            "aql",
            "li"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "mind",
            "having"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "uysiz",
          "english": "homeless — “house-less”",
          "breakdown": [
            "uy",
            "siz"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "house",
            "without"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "do'stlik",
          "english": "friendship",
          "breakdown": [
            "do'st",
            "lik"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "friend",
            "-ness / -ship"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "Bonus brick: -xona",
      "body": [
        "Borrowed from Persian: **-xona** means “the place for it”. *kasal* (sick) makes **kasalxona** — hospital. *osh* (plov) makes **oshxona** — kitchen. And *choy* makes **choyxona** — the teahouse waiting for you on the city map.",
        "Spot these bricks on signs and half the street names of Tashkent decode themselves."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "choyxona",
          "english": "teahouse — “tea-place”",
          "breakdown": [
            "choy",
            "xona"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "tea",
            "place for"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "kasalxona",
          "english": "hospital — “sick-place”",
          "breakdown": [
            "kasal",
            "xona"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "sick",
            "place for"
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "exercises": [
    {
      "id": "choice-worker",
      "engine": "choice",
      "instruction": "ish means “work”. So a worker is…",
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "ishchi",
          "correct": true,
          "explain": "-chi makes the doer: work → worker."
        },
        {
          "text": "ishli",
          "explain": "-li means “having” — that would be something like “having work”."
        },
        {
          "text": "ishsiz",
          "explain": "-siz means “without” — ishsiz is jobless, the opposite!"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "build-friendship",
      "engine": "build",
      "instruction": "Build “friendship” from do'st (friend)",
      "tokens": [
        "do'st",
        "lik"
      ],
      "decoys": [
        "chi",
        "siz"
      ],
      "joiner": "",
      "audioText": "do'stlik",
      "translation": "do'stlik — friendship"
    },
    {
      "id": "choice-sugarfree",
      "engine": "choice",
      "instruction": "shakar means “sugar”. Tea without sugar is choy…",
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "shakarsiz",
          "correct": true,
          "explain": "-siz: without sugar. Useful at every choyxona."
        },
        {
          "text": "shakarli",
          "explain": "-li means WITH sugar — the sweet opposite."
        },
        {
          "text": "shakarchi",
          "explain": "-chi makes a person — a sugar-seller!"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "build-teahouse",
      "engine": "build",
      "instruction": "Build “teahouse” — the place for tea",
      "tokens": [
        "choy",
        "xona"
      ],
      "decoys": [
        "lik",
        "chi"
      ],
      "joiner": "",
      "audioText": "choyxona",
      "translation": "choyxona — teahouse"
    }
  ],
  "wrapUp": "-chi makes the person, -li makes “with”, -siz makes “without”, -lik makes the idea, and -xona makes the place. One root, a whole word family."
}
